reviewText:
Sokoban-style game with a novel twist. Unfortunately, the game is plagued by a combination of slippery controls and no undo button. Slippery controls aren't an issue with undo, and lack of undo isn't a problem with tight controls.  When a game has both, it crosses the line from fun to frustrating very quickly.

I played the first 15 levels, and none of the puzzles took more than a couple seconds to find the solution. Executing always took much longer than it should have.

If you can get past the slippery controls, this could be a fun little game, especially for the price. As it is, that was a dealbreaker for me.

Update: Don't buy this, I refunded because I don't want to support this behaviour. They just released GooCubelets 2 only two months after releasing the first one, instead of updating the first game. And here's their third game a month and a half after the second!

4 / 10 - It's not worth more than the $1 they're asking for.
Pros:
It's easy to control the cube(s).
Some good puzzles, they can get slightly difficult.
50 puzzles.
Lets you choose which monitor to run the game on, resolution, overall quality and windowed mode.
Rebindable inputs, although it doesn't detect gamepads.
Some physics, but the results are completely static.
Cons:
Doesn't currently support gamepads, but you could use a third-party program such as Joy2Key or XPadder.
Music gets repetitive, isn't great. Just mute it and listen to something else.
The background on everything is pure white. It's blinding and very obnoxious. Trying to figure out puzzles while being blinded by the white background is not pleasant. There isn't a dark alternative and I highly recommend they make one.
The timer for individual levels starts while fading into the stage. There's no brief pause before beginning, meaning it could be hard to see where you're going at first if you're trying to get a good time.
Bronze, Silver and Gold medals for individual levels have ridiculous cutoffs. Gold usually being close to frame-perfect execution with the best solution, and Bronze isn't far behind.

reviewText:
To summarize, I wholehartedly recommend this awesome little time waster. SpaceChem is still my favorite puzzle game but this comes a close second. I'll definitely replay it every now and then.

Very clever puzzle game. It kinda looks like Sokoban but plays very different. As its key mechanic you have a one square gap between the pushing and the pushed block. If you're right next to another block you cannot push it. This leads to puzzles where you cannot move cubes along seemingly obvious paths because at some corner they don't leave you the two empty squares you need for the next push

Pros:
Three clever game mechanics (the standard gap push described above, pusher flock, second level with gap walking). Except for the trick needed for level 30 they are all self explanatory or well explained
A good variety of puzzles
The jelly effect rocks. I also like the general art style, with the white background, bright colors and the pretty unique soundtrack
Good challenge level, the game requires you to think without ever getting aggravatingly hard (unlike e.g. RUSH, where the last few levels are for masochists)
Very low price. If it had cost 3€ ( instead of 1€ ) I'd still have felt I got my money's worth
Cons:
Needs more levels :)
Level 30 really needs a hint text about the move you need to solve it. Without a hint from KipofMudd I would never have stumbled across it, it's just too counter-intuitive to normal physics think
Noticable lack of an undo button, leads to time sink situations when you try to experiment (level 30, I'm looking at you). Would take the fun out of level 50, so please no undo button on that level

reviewText:
The puzzles in this game were wonderful.  They artfully challenged me and my spatial thinking abilities, yet they never presented insurmountable challenges.

On the other hand, the controls aren't quite satisfactory.  On one level, after I figured out the solution, it still took me about 32 FREAKING MINUTES to beat the level.  For comparison, almost every level is easily passable within 2 minutes, if you know the solution, and this level is no exception.

Overall, though, this is a fantastic game (and the music is quite good as well).  For such a cheap game, it's well worth your time.

reviewText:
Sokoban Transport Puzzle (made with Unity Engine) with the added Annoyance that you can't move Boxes(GooCubelets) but also need to take a run-up to move the Boxes(GooCubelets). This also means stepping near a Box(GooCubelet) automatically pushes it even if you not intended to do.

The second Annoyance is that the Times are too tight, even if you do it very fast, you will only get a Bronze Medal awarded. But other than many other such Unity-Games at least Controller is supported in this one. It would perhaps be a nice Game for a Mobile Phone or Tablet, but definitely not for playing on TV even if Controller is supported.

I played till Level 25 and got bored very fast and also that large bright-white really hurted my Night-Creature-Eyes. I would give it a Neutral Rating, but unfortunately Steam only has Thumb up/down, so by applying the typical round down it's a Thumb down.

reviewText: This game has really bad controls, no undo button, and even though you can quickly find the solution, since there are bad controls and no undo button, it takes forever! reviewText:
tl;dr: GooCubelets is a little like Sokoban, but the jelly cubes have to be pushed onto squares matching their color to complete the levels. Completing the levels as quickly as possible is best. Try to buy GooCubelets when it is in your price range.

Disclaimer: As of this writing, I've played GooCubelets once and I've  only played up to level 14, so I'm not sure what mechanics might be introduced later on.

My opinion regarding GooCubelets' good and bad elements...
The good:
puzzle game with jiggly jelly cubes
music is pretty good. I did not find it distracting or unpleasant.
price was very low when I bought it on sale
interesting mechanics: to move a cube, you move your green gummi cube toward the cube from two squares away, which will bounce the cube over one square.
bronze, silver, and gold awards for each level!
challenging!
The not so good:
one wrong move and the level must be restarted
mechanics take some getting used to: to move a cube away from the edge of the board, it has to be at least two squares away from the edge
the time required to get even the bronze award is half as many seconds as what seemed like a fast run to me
music changes are relatively infrequent.
the camera takes some getting used to and is still suboptimal for some things
bronze, silver, and gold awards for short times on each level! However, each requires meeting or beating a preset time.
User Interface is awkward, but charming in its presentation.
challenging!
I recommend this game if you enjoy pushing colored gummi cubes around, enjoy puzzle games, enjoy finding the optimal path to get the fastest time, and/or enjoy challenges.

If you lose your temper easily, meditation might be a good way to clear and calm your mind before you take on the challenge that is GooCubelets.

reviewText:
I really liked this game, awesome puzzle-platformer, but there's a few problems:

- Controls can be a bit awkward, but they're part of the mechanic, basically, everytime you move from one square to another and get next to another cube, you will push that cube one square if there's space, it's very different from other games and takes time to get used to.

- No rewind or undo function, and this is a puzzle game that you're going to constantly get stuck when you make mistakes, thanks to the controls and puzzle mechanic.

- The squares in the floor where you're supposed to place the cubes, may not appear for you because the game tries to use your integrated graphics card, you have to configure your dedicated card to run the game, check the discussions to know how.

Overall, these problems are not that important, and maybe they will fix them later.

reviewText: If you are really into these kinds of puzzles, what you see is what you get.  The mechanics work well, and the visuals are decent.  However, I just didn't find it engaging enough to keep me playing beyond the first several levels.  I just got bored pretty quickly.  You can easily reset a level by the back button on an xbox 360 controller, or the reset icon on upper-right if using a mouse.  I preferred keyboard controls best, rather than the D-pad on my controller, but was a little ackward to click with the mouse to reset or hit the back button on the nearby controller.  But levels are short and fairly easy to repeat from start if you make a mistake.  Still, an undo move button might have kept me engaged longer, but isn't a deal breaker.\n\nRan fine on my Windows 10, Alienware Alpha running full screen on my 47 TV.  No technical issues."

reviewText:
Product received for free

Pros
- Good in concept and in implementation
- Clean, pretty graphics
- Challenging and still fun

Cons
- For whatever reason the display keeps ripping, as if I had overclocked the refresh rate of my monitor. Keeps making me stuff and and ultimately ruins the game. Can't change graphics in-game
- Controls not really that sensitive, makes the game more challenging though
- Music gets repetitive
- Basically impossible to get a medal, timing is too punishing

Would recommend it if it didn't keep ripping
